  "local_port": 53808,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Where can I find a training data set (free or not) for patent/prior art search to train a deep learning engine to select relevant prior art/ patents?",
  "response": "Finding a suitable training dataset for patent/prior art search can be challenging due to the specialized nature of the task. However, there are several resources where you can obtain datasets, either free or paid, that can be used to train a deep learning engine for this purpose. Here are some options:\n\n### 1. **Free Datasets**\n   - **Google Patents Public Datasets**: Google provides public datasets related to patents, including full-text patents and metadata. These datasets can be accessed through Google BigQuery or downloaded directly.  \n     [Google Patents Public Datasets](https://cloud.google.com/public-datasets/google-patents)\n\n   - **European Patent Office (EPO) Open Data**: EPO offers free access to patent data, including bibliographic data, full-text patents, and citation information.  \n     [EPO Open Data](https://www.epo.org/searching-for-patents/data/open-data.html)\n\n   - **USPTO Bulk Data Downloads**: The United States Patent and Trademark Office (USPTO) provides bulk data downloads, including full-text patents, bibliographic data, and patent assignments.  \n     [USPTO Bulk Data](https://bulkdata.uspto.gov/)\n\n   - **The Lens Patent Data**: The Lens offers free access to a large collection of patent data, including full-text patents, citations, and family data.  \n     [The Lens Patent Data](https://www.lens.org/lens/)\n\n   - **PubMed Central**: While not specifically for patents, PubMed Central provides open-access articles that can be useful for prior art search, especially in the life sciences domain.  \n     [PubMed Central](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/)\n\n### 2. **Paid Datasets**\n   - **PatSeer**: PatSeer provides access to a comprehensive patent database with advanced search capabilities. It\u2019s a paid service but can be useful for obtaining high-quality patent data.  \n     [PatSeer](https://www.patseer.com/)\n\n   - **Derwent Innovation**: Derwent offers a paid patent database with advanced search and analytics tools. It\u2019s widely used in the industry for patent research.  \n     [Derwent Innovation](https://clarivate.com/derwent/solutions/derwent-innovation/)\n\n   - **LexisNexis PatentSight**: PatentSight provides access to a global patent database with advanced analytics. It\u2019s a paid service but offers high-quality data for training models.  \n     [PatentSight](https://www.patentsight.com/)\n\n   - **WIPO PATENTSCOPE**: While WIPO provides free access to international patent data through PATENTSCOPE, some advanced features and datasets may require a subscription.  \n     [WIPO PATENTSCOPE](https://patentscope.wipo.int/search/en/search.jsf)\n\n### 3. **Custom Datasets**\n   - **Interested Parties Data**: If you have access to a law firm, patent office, or company that handles patent searches, they may have proprietary datasets that can be used for training.\n   \n   - **Contributory Data Platforms**: Platforms like Kaggle or GitHub occasionally host datasets related to patents, either contributed by users or as part of competitions.\n\n### 4. **Other Considerations**\n   - **Data Cleaning and Preprocessing**: Patent data often requires significant preprocessing, including text extraction, normalization, and deduplication, before it can be used for training.\n   \n   - **Annotation**: If your task involves supervised learning, you may need to manually annotate patent documents with relevance labels or use existing citation data as a proxy for relevance.\n\n### 5. **Research Datasets**\n   - **PatentsView**: This is a free, open-source platform that provides access to U.S. patent data, including citations, inventors, and assignees.  \n     [PatentsView](https://www.patentsview.org/)\n\n   - **Microsoft Research Open Data**: Occasionally, Microsoft Research releases datasets related to patents and prior art.  \n     [Microsoft Research Open Data](https://msropendata.com/)\n\nBy leveraging these resources, you can build a robust dataset for training a deep learning model tailored to patent/prior art search.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
